{"id":"2110.01489","submitter":"Frank Quinn","authors":"Frank Quinn","title":"Object generators 1: set theory","comments":"24 pages, including table of contents. Replaces \"Object descriptors\n  and set theory''. Same content as the previous version, but notation changed\n  to be more consistent with standard usage. Some arguments streamlined. arXiv\n  admin note: substantial text overlap with arXiv:2009.08867","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.LO math.CT math.HO","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Object generators are generalizations of the `object' aspects of categories,\nand have much less structure than sets. This paper gives the technical\ndevelopment of the theory, but mainly focuses on the set theory located within\nit. The main result is that in this set theory there is an (almost)\nwell-founded pairing that is universal in the sense that any (almost)\nwell-founded pairing is isomorphic to a transitive subobject of this one. In\nparticular, if an axiom system includes the axiom of foundation then all models\nof it are equivalent to such subobjects. The universal well-founded pairing\nsatisfies the Zermillo-Fraenkel-Choice axioms, minus first-order logic, so it\nis also the maximal such theory. Maximality follows from the fact that its\n``universe'' does not support quantification.\n  We apply universality to show that a ZFC theory is either a truncation of the\nmaximal theory, or there is a ZFC set with a bijection to a subdomain of its\nuniverse that is not a ZFC set.\n  The sequel, 2210.07280, illustrates simplifications in everyday use of set\ntheory that make it almost as easy to use as naive set theory. It seems to be\nthe set theory that has been the de facto foundation for deductive mathematics\nfor the last century. This paper also illustrates the use of the general theory\nas a setting for category theory.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 4 Oct 2021 15:00:00 GMT"},{"ve